IVARSTEAD / THE BLEEDING STAIR — FIRE B PLANNING DOC
Gate 3, Fire B. The party's FIRST contact with the Dagon apocalypse and
with Gaelen the Root-Twister. Design bible; build the runnable module from
this. Companion: gate 3 (Fire B section), saijah 2, The Hound and the Wolf
(being de-rushed — see Section X), Npcs/new mythic dawn leader, Daedric path.

CORE DISCIPLINE FOR THIS MODULE (read first):
  This is an INTRODUCTION. It ADVANCES threads; it RESOLVES nothing
  personal. Saijah does NOT choose a patron here. Gaelen does NOT die here.
  The crossroads is LOADED, not fired. Two reveal layers, kept separate:
   - HARD PARTY REVEALS (concrete, landed this session): the Tower
     cosmology, Gaelen's multi-Tower campaign, that this is apocalypse-scale
     and he has been winning unopposed. The party LEAVES KNOWING they are
     now in the main plot.
   - PACED PERSONAL REALIZATION (slow, accumulating, finishes AFTER the
     module): Saijah's grief-knowledge that the gildergreens are one tree,
     that it is a Tower, that there is a heart she has never found. Bloom
     it over stations; let the conclusion complete on the road home.

=====================================================================
0. THE RELAUNCH (why this module is built the way it is)
=====================================================================
This is the campaign's reset to its ORIGINAL methodology after the gate-2
sprawl. Not new rules — a RESTORATION of how modules 1-8 already worked,
that the open-world detour made impossible to sustain. Hold three lines:
  - RE-CONTAIN THE FORM. One place, one escalating problem, a clean arc
    with a CURTAIN (Prologue -> 5 sections -> resolution -> door closes),
    ONE runsheet, ~3 sessions. Player freedom lives INSIDE these walls; it
    is not the walls. The unchosen fires escalate OFF-SCREEN as rumor, not
    prep. Never prep a continent again.
  - THE ENSEMBLE IS LOAD-BEARING BY CONSTRUCTION. Every party member, PCs
    and cart-crew, gets a beat that is theirs (Section IX). This is the
    practice the GM already had in the early modules; the sandbox is what
    diluted it. Engagement is rewarded; nobody is a passenger by design.
  - IT IS THE STORY'S RELAUNCH TOO. The Tower reveal recontextualizes the
    whole campaign — "the chaos was one story all along." The in-fiction
    "everything just got bigger and clearer" and the at-table "the game is
    firing again" are the SAME feeling, engineered to land together.

=====================================================================
I. THE COSMOLOGY (the thing the whole campaign has been hiding)
=====================================================================
THE TOWERS. Reality is held against Oblivion by world-pillars (Towers).
TWO of them matter here:
  - THE ELDERGLEAM is a Tower. It is ONE organism (a Pando — a single tree
    whose root network spans Skyrim and surfaces as the many gildergreens).
    Its true trunk/heart sits in a CAVE the party has never visited. The
    root network IS the land's planar immune system.
  - THE THROAT OF THE WORLD is a SEPARATE Tower (its own pillar; the
    Eldergleam's roots merely reach its peak). The Bleeding Stair is NOT the
    Eldergleam — it is the SAME corruption method applied to a DIFFERENT
    Tower.

THE GILDERGREEN NODES. Each surface gildergreen is an immune node / firewall.
  As Dagon's corruption spreads through the roots, every node it reaches
  tries to HALT and quarantine it — so the cult must corrupt each node
  INDIVIDUALLY to break the firewall and advance toward the heart. Every
  dying gildergreen the party has seen since ACT I is a FALLEN CIRCUIT
  BREAKER — a battle the Eldergleam already lost, node by node, while the
  party looked elsewhere. (Thornheart Grove, Act I = a node. The Solitude
  temple gildergreen, where Saijah recognized "the same corruption as
  Thornheart" = a node.) The corruption has advanced across the map in plain
  sight the entire campaign; no one read it as one war.

THE GRADIENT (the find-the-heart engine). Nodes corrupt SLOWER the CLOSER
  they are to the true heart (closer = stronger). Solitude/Haafingar corrupts
  slowly (strong, near the heart); the Rift and Eastmarch fell first (far,
  weak — which is why the migraine has always pointed southeast, toward the
  weakest dying nodes). The disease is a map of itself: follow the slowing
  toward the heart, NORTHWEST. [GM TBD: exact cave location — gradient points
  Haafingar-ward; pin it when the heart module is built.]

THE THREE RESPONSES = SAIJAH'S THREE PATRONS (the campaign thesis):
  - KYNARETH: heal the whole organism — go to the heart, endure, mercy.
  - HIRCINE: cull the infected branches — "the forest sheds the dead branch;
    a sick herd is culled." Amputation. Loss as strategy.
  - GAELEN/DAGON: unmake the Tower to "free" it from the prison of static law.
  Heal it, prune it, or unmake it. One dying super-organism, three theologies,
  and Saijah is the vessel who must pick.

=====================================================================
II. GAELEN — WHY HE SURVIVES (it is hubris, not GM fiat)
=====================================================================
Gaelen's PRIMARY operation — corrupting the Eldergleam Tower — has gone
PERFECTLY, quietly, for the whole campaign, with no one opposing him. So he
got ambitious: unopposed, why not corrupt MULTIPLE Towers at once? The Throat
(this module) is his GREEDY SECOND PROJECT.

THE ESCAPE, structurally: the win condition is DISRUPTING the Throat ritual,
not killing Gaelen. Disruption only swats his overextension — his perfect
primary plan at the Eldergleam is untouched. He FALLS BACK to the thing that
is still working, phasing into the destabilized Time-Wound (his carved soul
and Daedric grafts make him half out of linear time already; the collapse
RELEASES him). The players did not beat him; they interrupted a man who
reached for a second prize because he thought himself unopposed. He recurs
with a grievance now attached: "you finally showed up." Curious, not
vengeful — scarier.
  FRAME THE OBJECTIVE OUT LOUD AS THE RITUAL, never as Gaelen's head. If the
  players think the mission is "kill Gaelen," his escape feels like a robbery.
  If they know it is "stop the Unmaking / save the Throat," his escape is just
  Thursday.

GAELEN'S INTRO (he must land UNSETTLING, not evil): the warm, sincere,
reasonable CENTER of an apocalypse. He talks like an ally trying to get
compatriots to stop suffering for a stagnant world. The Aedra gave mortals a
CELL (linear time, fragile flesh); Dagon offers the KEY; the Unmaking is
HEALING. Plant the QUIET WISH — overheard when he does not know anyone is
listening, to no one: "I want it to be perfect. Please... let it be perfect."
Not a plea, not a crack in a mask — the closest thing his altered architecture
has to hope. The players will project grief onto it; every projection is
slightly wrong. He should leave the table unable to dismiss him.

THE THEOLOGICAL TRAP ON SAIJAH: Gaelen is AWARE of her (her migraine is a
beacon through the corrupted leylines). He offers her a vision of "liberated
nature" — forests that burn and regrow in seconds, animals mutating and
evolving endlessly — versus Kynareth's "static preservation." This is the
INTELLECTUAL seduction (new, his — separate from Hircine's offer of teeth).

=====================================================================
III. THE JOURNEY — THE TWO DRAGONS YOU CANNOT FIGHT
=====================================================================
TWO dragons, not one — deliberately, so the party does not even consider a
brawl. Two at once is unwinnable on open ground, and the point is to teach
that: the only play is to HIDE. Avoiding them matters five ways: varies the
rhythm (the last two dragons were fights); denies Bjorn the souls (his arc
is paced by other means now — see below); teaches that dragons OWN the sky
(Tier-1 spillover, the cost of NOT taking the Dragonstone fire); STALLS
HIRCINE'S COURTSHIP (Section V — no kill, no fresh hook); and it is the
stage for BJORN'S AWAKENING.

DETECTION AS A CLOCK (not one roll): the dragons hunt/feed, not scripted to
engage. The party goes quiet — break line of sight, kill the lanterns, still
the cart, mask heat/sound/magic. Run escalating group Agility/Guile checks
where the PARTY'S OWN ASSETS are the complications: Mable spooks, GEAR hums,
Alfonso's rot-aura carries downwind, a wet cough from camp. Each member
manages their own tell. The dragons' awareness ticks up on failures; blow
it and you are exposed under TWO dragons with the cart in the blast line —
a near-unsurvivable punishment, which is the teeth that keep them hiding.

BJORN'S AWAKENING (the heart of the journey — Mila is the trigger):
  At the worst moment of the hide, the danger reaches MILA — a dragon's
  pass, falling debris, a beast flushed toward the cart, something the old
  carter cannot possibly reach in time. And he reaches it anyway. For one
  impossible instant the War-Hound's speed wakes in him — he crosses ground
  no old man could cross, puts his body between the child and the death,
  and is standing there, breathing hard, younger in the eyes than he was a
  second ago, not understanding what just happened. NOT for the world. NOT
  for glory. For one child he refuses to be too late for. This is the first
  flicker of the dragon-soul stirring, and it is witnessed (by whom, and
  whether anyone names it, is a free beat). Kyboh was meant to ARGUE him
  back; instead a child in danger does what no argument could. The fuse is
  lit here. See Section IX-B for the full Dragon-Born progression.

=====================================================================
IV. THE BLEEDING STAIR — OVER-THE-TOP COSMIC HORROR
=====================================================================
The spectacle is TIME BREAKING, escalating per Waystone:
  - Waystone 1: subtle. Snow falls upward a moment. A footprint appears
    before the foot.
  - Waystones 3-4: afterimages a half-second behind; a sentence someone said
    replays from the rocks in their own voice.
  - Near the summit: full temporal distortion as a COMBAT HAZARD — initiative
    reshuffles mid-fight; a character acts twice then loses the next turn;
    a spell cast this round resolves NEXT round; damage lands before the
    attack is declared.
THE CHEATED GAME: the Dagonite cultists WEAPONIZE it — stolen turns, doubled
  moves, striking out of sequence. This is YLVA'S hook: Burning Indignation,
  the Referee's Wrath. She does not feel cosmic horror; she feels a RIGGED
  GAME and enforces the rules. The most theologically serious person on the
  Stair about why the Unmaking is wrong is the werewolf — Gaelen wants to
  dissolve the laws; Ylva's whole faith is that the laws make the game sacred.
  VARON agrees from the opposite pole (Shadowscale doctrine kills clean inside
  the rules of time). The two who cannot stand each other ALIGN here. Give
  Ylva and Gaelen one exchange — both liturgies, out loud.

=====================================================================
V. SAIJAH AT IVARSTEAD — ADVANCE ONLY (the core of the redo)
=====================================================================
THE DOUBLE MIGRAINE (mechanical). She is wired into the root network and here
feels TWO Towers corrupted at once (the Eldergleam she always feels + the
Throat under fresh assault). TRIGGER: the instant she touches the first black
sap. EFFECT while in the corrupted zone (the whole Stair):
    -2 Guile, -2 Agility, AND +2 damage taken.
Sustained, brutal, FELT BY THE PLAYER — which is exactly what gives Hircine's
"I can make it stop" its hook. (Replaces/over-rides the -1 city penalty here.)

THE PACED REVEAL (stations, NOT one "aha" — the lesson):
  1. Road / early Stair: the black sap NAGS — familiar, can't place it. An
     itch, not a recognition.
  2. Deeper: she places the SIGNATURE — "I've felt this before" (Thornheart,
     Solitude) — but reads it as coincidence. Two points, no pattern.
  3. The migraine DOUBLES: two simultaneous sources, which makes no sense to
     her. The -2/-2/+2 hits. Something is deeply wrong; she does not know what.
  4. Gaelen's seduction: he lets SCALE slip — "prisons," freeing "more than
     one," implies he works elsewhere. A clue she cannot yet hold.
  5. The Greybeards: the masters venerate the Throat as sacred — they hand
     the party the word TOWER (the hard reveal).
  6. AFTER, on the road (NOT in the module): gildergreens + the Throat +
     "Tower" + TWO migraines finally assemble — one tree, it is a Tower, TWO
     Towers are under attack, there is a heart she has never found. The
     module PLANTS; the realization GROWS.

KYNARETH FIRST, THEN HIRCINE (strict order — the tragedy depends on it):

  (A) KYNARETH'S REVEAL — at/near the monastery (Kyne's peak, goddess of the
  Voice). The FIRST NEW THING she has ever given (after all the "same
  instructions" frustration). Cryptic, non-verbal: she shows Saijah something
  about BJORN — a thread pulling a great soul toward SOVNGARDE to face ALDUIN.
  NOT words, NOT a quest-objective: an IMAGE SAIJAH CANNOT DECODE YET (a wind
  carrying a soul upward; the sense that her enduring MATTERS to the end of
  the world). It threads the Dragonborn question through Saijah without ever
  naming it — a FEELING about Bjorn, never a label, so the no-one-can-confirm-
  the-Dragonborn rule holds. This is the REASON TO ENDURE THE PAIN.

  (B) HIRCINE'S TEMPTATION — after Kynareth, toward the summit. He offers to
  QUIET THE MIGRAINE (end the -2/-2/+2 agony the player has suffered all
  climb). THE HIDDEN COST he will not mention: silencing the pain silences
  KYNARETH — the root-network channel that screams is the same one the
  goddess speaks through (the Mzinchaleft principle: "if the roots can't
  reach her, Kynareth can't reach her; silence is not always peace"). He
  offers RELIEF THAT SEVERS, the morning after Kynareth finally spoke. He
  does not lie; he just does not say that part. NO weredog offer-as-choice
  here — the senses intensify, the weredog is GLIMPSED, nothing is decided.

  YLVA: RIVALRY ignites (competition, NOT bond, NOT rebound). She smells
  Hircine's favor on Saijah and turns it into a contest — out-hunt, out-kill,
  prove to the Hunter who the real predator is. (The BOND must grow over
  later sessions before the rebound can land; do not rush it.)

  HARD STOPS for this module: no patron chosen. No weredog offer-as-yes/no.
  No transformation. No artifact (Hawk) crystallization. No Ylva rebound. The
  four-hander crossroads RESOLUTION scene does NOT happen here — it moves to
  the first real reckoning (Gaelen-kill at the heart OR the Mehrunes' Razor
  moment, whichever lands first).

